item.title: As Countries Ease Coronavirus Lockdowns, New Cases Emerge
item.description: Some governors sought more help from Washington as they moved to restart their economies, while new clusters of coronavirus infections emerged in the Middle East and Asia after authorities loosened lockdowns.

item.title: Militants Attack Afghan Hospital, Killing Babies
item.description: Militants wearing police uniforms stormed a hospital in Afghanistan, killing at least 16 people, including two babies, amid an escalation in violence that threatens to undermine U.S. efforts to extricate itself from its longest war.

item.title: South Korea's Coronavirus Efforts Spark LGBT Privacy Concerns
item.description: After a fresh outbreak was traced to a man who visited gay bars in Seoul in early May, health officials’ contact-tracing tactics have raised fears of among LGBT people already facing stigmatization, advocacy groups say.

item.title: Turkey Strains to Ward Off Currency Crisis
item.description: The coronavirus pandemic threatens to push Turkey into a full-blown balance-of-payments crisis, leaving President Recep Tayyip Erdogan facing one of the biggest challenges in his 18-year rule.

item.title: On the Ground in Wuhan, Signs of China Stalling Probe of Coronavirus Origins
item.description: Beijing at first appeared to be homing in fast on the source of the virus. It is now impeding international efforts to find it amid a U.S. push to blame China for the pandemic, health experts and officials say. Chinese officials have yet to share data on animals sampled at the Huanan market.

item.title: Is It Safe to Reopen Schools? Europe Is About to Find Out
item.description: The world is trying to figure out how to reopen schools during a coronavirus pandemic. In Europe, millions of children are returning to classrooms, turning the continent into a giant lab for what works and what doesn’t.
